etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in Jerome Turler (1550–1602). From down- + the past participle of fall, after to fall down

definitions: That has fallen from an upright or elevated position; that has collapsed.
That has lost power, prosperity, status, etc.; diminished or defeated.
Of a person, his or her appearance: expressing or overwhelmed by despondency, sorrow, discouragement, etc.
